label.value: intracerebral hemorrhage induced by collagenase injection

value.value: This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is experimental intracerebral hemorrhage induced by collagenase injection into the cerebrum, a method used to model intracerebral hemorrhage in laboratory animals. Severity of hemorrhage can be controlled by the amount of collagenase injected. For example 0.23 U of bacterial collagenase VII-S injected into rat striatum causes a moderate intracerebral hemorrhage, and 0.6 U of bacterial collagenase VII-S injected into rat striatum causes severe intracerebral hemorrhage.

This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is glycerol, a trihydroxy sugar alcohol that is an intermediate in carbohydrate and lipid metabolism. Glycerol is used as a solvent, emollient, pharmaceutical agent, and sweetening agent.

This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is a specific amount of glycerol dissolved in saline (0.9% sodium chloride solution). Glycerol is a trihydroxy sugar alcohol that is used as a solvent, emollient, pharmaceutical agent, and sweetening agent.

This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is a thoracic aortic constriction sham procedure, which follows the same surgical process as a thoracic aortic constriction without blocking the aorta.

This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is a hyperbaric chamber, which raises atmospheric pressure to simulate atmospheric conditions below sea level or underwater. A hyperbaric chamber may use ambient air at high pressure (hyperbaric air) or air with high oxygen content at high pressure (hyperbaric oxygen therapy).
This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is citrate buffer, a combination of sodium citrate dihydrate and citric acid in water to form a solution with a pH range of 3.0 to 6.2.

This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is ochratoxin A, a phenylalanine derivative that is a nephrotoxic, carcinogenic mycotoxin. Ochratoxin A is among the most widely occurring food-contaminating mycotoxins, produced by Aspergillus ochraceus, Aspergillus carbonarius and Penicillium verrucosum.
This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is 3-chloro-1,2-propanediol, a chlorinated propanediol with antifertility activity in males used as a chemosterilant in rodents.

This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is a drink made up of water and a specified amount of 3-chloro-1,2-propanediol, a chlorinated propanediol with antifertility activity in males used as a chemosterilant in rodents.

This is any condition in which the main influencing factor is minocycline, a semi-synthetic second-generation tetracycline and a broad-spectrum antibiotic. Minocycline has a dimethylamino group at position 7 and lacks the methyl and hydroxy groups at position 5, which makes it effective against tetracycline-resistant staphylococcus infections.
Compound that can link two or more polymer chains.
A cross-linking reagent with identical reactive groups at each end of the spacer arm.
A cross-linking reagent with at least two different reactive groups.
A cross-linking reagent causing direct conjugation without becoming part of the final cross-link between the target molecules.
An attribute describing a cross-linker.
Indicates that a cross-linker is deuterium labelled.
Indicates that a cross-linker is hydrolyzed, for example for NHS-type reagents -C(=O)-NHS was converted to -C(=O)-OH.
Indicates that a cross-linker is amidated.
Indicates that a cross-linker is membrane permeable.
Indicates that a cross-linker is hydrophilic.
Indicates that a cross-linker is fluorescent.
Indicates that a cross-linker is cleavable.
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable.
Indicates that a cross-linker is mass-spectrometrically cleavable, i.e. contains a MS2 labile bond leading to fragments detected in MS3.
Indicates that a cross-linker facilitates enrichment.
Indicates that a cross-linker is iodinatable, e.g. for autoradiographic detection by radio-labelling with J-131.
Indicates a dead-end modification that was amidated by an ammonium salt, like e.g. bicarbonate, phosphate, chloride, for example for NHS-type reagents -C(=O)-NHS was converted to -C(=O)-NH2.
Indicates a dead-end modification that was amidated by Tris(hydroxymethyl)-aminomethane, for example for NHS-type reagents -C(=O)-NHS was converted to -C(=O)-NHC(CH2OH)3.

Indicates that a cross-linker contains a cleavable S-S bond, which is chemically cleavable by reducing agents like e.g. thiols, beta-mercaptoethanol, dithiothreitol (DTT), mercaptomethylamine or Tris(2-carboxyethyl)phosphin (TCEP).
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by the oxidizing agent periodate.
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by hydroxylamine.
Indicates that a reactive group reacts with specific functional groups.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with primary amino (-NH2) groups.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with sulfhydryl (-SH) groups.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with carboxyl (-COOH) groups.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with aldehyde (-CHO) or carbonyl (-CO) groups.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with hydroxyl (-OH) groups.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with azide (-N3) groups.
Indicates that a cross-linker is cleavable by light.
Indicates that a cross-linker is mass-spectrometrically cleavable by collission induced dissociation.
Indicates that a cross-linker is labelled with carbon-13.
Indicates that a cross-linker is non-selective (i.e. can react with different amino acids, but also with DNA/RNA and carbohydrates (aldehyde reactive)).
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by the reducing agent DTT (dithiothreitol).
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by ammonium hydroxide.
Indicates that a cross-linker is mass-spectrometrically cleavable by in-source decay.
Indicates that a cross-linker is mass-spectrometrically cleavable (reducible) by thiols.
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by the reducing agent TCEP (Tris(2-carboxyethyl)phosphin).
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by the reducing agent mercaptoethanol.
Indicates that a cross-linker is mass defect labelled.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with thioether (R1-S-R2) groups.
